ircuit: A Festival Career from Czech Dream to Czech Peace -- t12 Material Traces of Lebanon: A Documentary Aesthetics of Feeling in the Art Gallery -- t13 Autonomous Navigation? Multiplicity and Self-reflexive Aesthetics in Sergio Basso’s Documentary Film Giallo a Milano and Web Documentary Made in Chinatown -- t14 Fukushima and the Shifting Conventions of Documentary: From Broadcast to Social Media Netizenship -- t15 Independent Documentaries and Online Uses in China: From Cinephilia to Activism -- tConclusion -- tNotes on the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPresents in-depth case studies focusing on major aspects of post-1990 documentary practices and stylesIn a post-1990 context of unrivalled creativity in documentary filmmaking, what does ‘independence’ really mean? With a broad selection of contributors, this is the first collection of in-depth case studies to cut across different media, formats, subject matters, purposes and national divides. Writing from a wide range of academic perspectives, contributors shed new light on historical, theoretical and empirical issues concerning independent documentary, to better comprehend the radical transformations of the form over the past twenty-five years. While the digital turn has been widely acknowledged as decisive in reshaping film practices, especially independent ones, this anthology aims at assessing its consequences without overestimating the impact of technology on other political, economic, social and cultural changes. Continuities as well as breaks are therefore put in perspective, with a particular focus on the interactions between these new practices and the established film and television industries. Divided into three main sections on ‘History and Spaces of Resistance’, ‘The Personal Experience’ and ‘Displacement, Participation and Spectatorship’, Post-1990 Documentary: Reconfiguring Independence provides an innovative interpretation of under-studied subject matters and styles, and rare analysis of differing production, distribution and exhibition strategies. It not only helps to rethink the notion of independence, but also contributes to a fundamental change in our perception of documentary filmmaking.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aDocumentary filmsxHistory and criticism. 4aFilm, Media & Cultural Studies. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / Direction & Production.2bisacsh1 aBroderick, Mick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aByg, Barton, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChung, Hilary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeprez, Camille, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFeigelson, Kristian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGalmard, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoursat, Juliette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHughes, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIngham, Mike, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJacobs, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLuciano, Bernadette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaasdorp, Liani, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorag, Raya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPernin, Judith, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aPernin, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPetty, Sheila, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTakahashi, Tess, 